const e="liquidity-bid-ask",i="Liquidity & Bid-Ask Spread",t="7 min",o=[{screen_type:"hook",visual:"ðŸšªðŸ”’",headline:"Your option is up 200%... but nobody will buy it",text:"You're trying to sell for $5. Bid is $2.50. Ask is $7.50. The spread is $5 - that's 100% of value! This is illiquid hell. Let's make sure you never get trapped."},{screen_type:"definition",headline:"What is Liquidity?",text:"LIQUIDITY = how easily you can buy/sell an option without moving the price. HIGH LIQUIDITY = tight bid-ask spread ($0.05-0.10), instant fills. LOW LIQUIDITY = wide spread ($1+), hard to exit. BID = highest price buyers offer. ASK = lowest price sellers want. SPREAD = Ask - Bid.",visual:"ðŸ’§",highlight_words:["LIQUIDITY","bid-ask spread","BID","ASK","SPREAD"]},{screen_type:"key_terms",headline:"Liquidity Terms",cards:[{term:"Bid-Ask Spread",definition:"Difference between bid (buy price) and ask (sell price)",example:"Bid $4.90, Ask $5.10 = $0.20 spread (good!). Bid $3.00, Ask $6.00 = $3 spread (terrible - avoid!)."},{term:"Open Interest",definition:"Total number of outstanding option contracts",example:"Open interest 10,000+ = liquid, easy to trade. Open interest 50 = illiquid, avoid. Check before buying!"},{term:"Slippage",definition:"Loss due to buying at ask and selling at bid",example:"You pay $5.10 (ask), sell at $4.90 (bid) = $0.20 instant loss per share Ã— 100 = $20 per contract. Wide spreads = expensive slippage."}]},{screen_type:"analogy",headline:"Think of it like selling concert tickets",text:"You have Taylor Swift tickets you want to sell. Two scenarios...",interactive:"tap_to_reveal",reveal_sections:[{label:"Venue with 50,000 fans (high liquidity)",content:"Tons of buyers. You post for $200, someone buys in 10 seconds. Bid $199, ask $201 = $2 spread. Easy exit, fair price. This is liquid options (SPY, AAPL, TSLA)."},{label:"Venue with 50 fans (low liquidity)",content:"Few buyers. You post for $200. Highest offer is $100. You're stuck - sell at 50% loss or hold forever. Bid $100, ask $200 = $100 spread. This is illiquid options."},{label:"This is option liquidity",content:"High volume + tight spread = easy to trade. Low volume + wide spread = trapped in position. Always check before buying!"}]},{screen_type:"multiple_choice",question:"An option shows: Bid $7.50, Ask $7.65. Is this liquid?",options:["No - spread is too wide","Yes - spread is only $0.15","Can't tell from this info","Spreads don't matter"],correct:1,xp_reward:10,explanation_correct:"Great eye! $0.15 spread on a $7.50 option = 2% slippage. That's excellent. You can enter and exit easily. Rule of thumb: spread should be <5% of option price. This is 2% = very liquid. Green light!",explanation_wrong:"Let's calculate: $0.15 spread Ã· $7.50 midpoint = 2% slippage. That's tight! Under 5% = liquid. Under 2% = very liquid. This option trades easily. Compare to illiquid: bid $3, ask $7 = 57% spread = nightmare!"},{screen_type:"multiple_choice",question:"You're choosing between two similar options. A) Volume 5,000, Spread $0.10. B) Volume 50, Spread $2.50. Which do you trade?",options:["B - lower volume means less competition","A - high volume and tight spread","Both are fine","Volume doesn't matter"],correct:1,xp_reward:10,explanation_correct:"Always pick liquidity! Option A: 5,000 volume = lots of traders = easy exit. $0.10 spread = minimal slippage. Option B: 50 volume = ghost town. $2.50 spread = you lose $250 just entering/exiting per contract. Never trade illiquid options!",explanation_wrong:"Liquidity = your emergency exit. High volume (5,000+) = instant fills. Tight spread ($0.10) = fair pricing. Low volume (50) + wide spread ($2.50) = you're trapped. Even if your trade is right, you lose to the spread. Avoid!"},{screen_type:"scenario",question:"You want to day trade options. Which strike should you choose?",options:["Far OTM (cheap but illiquid)","ATM or slightly OTM (most liquid)","Deep ITM (safe but illiquid)","Doesn't matter for day trading"],correct:1,xp_reward:15,explanation_correct:"Perfect for day trading! ATM and slightly OTM options have the MOST volume and tightest spreads. You can enter/exit fast. Far OTM and deep ITM = wider spreads = harder to trade quickly. Day traders need liquidity!",explanation_wrong:"Day trading requires liquidity because you're entering/exiting same day. ATM options have highest volume (most traders focus here). Far OTM = cheap but wide spreads = you lose to slippage. Deep ITM = expensive, low volume. Stick to ATM/near ATM for day trading."},{screen_type:"scenario",question:"You bought an option with $1 spread. It's now profitable, but spread is still $1. You want to sell. What do you do?",options:["Sell at bid - take the hit","Place limit order between bid and ask - try for better fill","Hold until spread tightens","Exercise the option"],correct:1,xp_reward:15,explanation_correct:"Smart! Don't sell at bid immediately. Place limit order at midpoint or slightly below. Market makers may fill you for better price. Example: bid $4, ask $5, place limit $4.50. Might wait 5-10 min, but save $50 per contract. Patience pays!",explanation_wrong:"Wide spread = negotiate. Bid $4, ask $5 = midpoint $4.50. Place limit sell at $4.50. Market makers compete to fill orders. You might get $4.40-4.60 instead of $4. Never accept bid price immediately on wide spreads - always try midpoint first!"},{screen_type:"scenario",question:"You found a perfect setup but open interest is only 100. What's the risk?",options:["No risk - open interest doesn't matter","You might not be able to exit when you want to","The option will expire worthless","Your broker will reject the order"],correct:1,xp_reward:15,explanation_correct:"Major risk! Open interest 100 = almost nobody trading. When you need to exit, there might be no buyers. You're stuck holding to expiration or accepting terrible bid price. Rule: avoid options with <1,000 open interest. Some traders require 5,000+.",explanation_wrong:"Low open interest = liquidity trap. Only 100 contracts exist = maybe 10-20 active traders. When you want to sell, you might be the ONLY seller with no buyers. Price can gap against you. Always check open interest before buying - it's your exit strategy!"},{screen_type:"summary_cards",headline:"Liquidity Checklist",cards:[{front:"Before buying ANY option, check...",back:"1) Bid-ask spread (<5% of price), 2) Volume (today's trading, want 1,000+), 3) Open interest (total contracts, want 1,000+). All three must pass. No exceptions."},{front:"Which options are most liquid?",back:"SPY, QQQ, AAPL, MSFT, TSLA, NVDA - the mega caps. ATM and slightly OTM strikes. Monthly expirations (not weeklies far out). These trade like clockwork."},{front:"What if you're stuck in illiquid option?",back:"1) Place limit order at midpoint, wait hours/days, 2) Sell at bid and take the loss, 3) Hold to expiration if ITM, 4) Lesson learned: check liquidity BEFORE buying!"}]},{screen_type:"celebration",xp_earned:70,total_xp:960,badge:"ðŸ’§ Liquidity Hunter",badge_description:"You'll never get trapped in illiquid options!",celebration_message:"Awesome! You now know how to avoid one of the biggest beginner traps. Next: choosing the right expiration date for your strategy.",streak_bonus:!1,next_lesson_preview:{title:"Choosing Expiration Dates",description:"Learn when to use weeklies, monthlies, or LEAPS for maximum edge",unlock_status:"unlocked"}}],s={lesson_id:e,title:i,estimated_time:t,screens:o};export{s as default,t as estimated_time,e as lesson_id,o as screens,i as title};
